                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="sole" script="unknown">The manuscript is beautifully
                                written in a large, clear and distinct hand. <name type="person"
                                    key="SteKar001">Stefan Karlsson</name> finds that this hand is
                                identical with the one who, among other manuscripts, wrote the <ref
                                    type="ms">AM 122 a fol</ref>. </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <additions>The originally blank fol. 1r contain one to six marginalia
                            concerning the content. These are written in <date from="1600" to="1699"
                                >the seventeenth century</date> by an untrained hand. Among younger
                            additions to the manucript is the name Ásmundur Klemensson, and a man
                            with this unusual name appears in various sources from the years <date
                                from="1497" to="1530">1497-1530</date>.</additions>
                        <accMat>On an AM-slip <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni
                                Magnússon</name> wrote: <q xml:lang="da">Denne bog haver universitas
                                Hafniensis laant mig ex Bibliothecâ Resenianâ <date when="1706"
                                    >1706</date>. og bör den af mig uskaddet at restitueres. A
                                Magnussen</q>. Another slip, written by <name type="person"
                                key="PedRes001">Peder Resen</name> is attached: <q xml:lang="la"
                                >Codex islandicus mss. in pergamento: agit de aliis atq<ex>ve</ex>
                                aliis Islandiæ Episcopis præsertim de Gudmundo Eposcopo Ariæ filio.
                                Petri Resenii <date when="1685">1685</date>
                            </q>. The slip was possibly a former fly-leaf</accMat>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin notBefore="1330" notAfter="1350">The manuscript was written in
                                <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace> in the period <origDate
                                notBefore="1330" notAfter="1350" evidence="conjecture"
                                >1330-1350</origDate> (<bibl>
                                <ref type="secondary" target="EA-B6">Stefán Karlsson 1983</ref>
                                <biblScope unit="page">xli</biblScope>
                            </bibl>). Kålund's dating: <date notBefore="1290" notAfter="1310"
                                evidence="conjecture">ca. 1300</date> (<bibl>
                                <ref type="secondary" target="KKKat">Katalog</ref>
                                <biblScope unit="volume">I</biblScope>
                                <biblScope unit="page">604</biblScope>
                            </bibl>).</origin>
                        <provenance>The manuscript has belonged to <name type="person"
                                key="PedRes001">Peder Resen</name>, from whom it got its nickname.
                            Nothing is known of the earlier history of the manuscript.</provenance>
                        <acquisition>AM 399 4to was one of the manuscripts Peder Resen presented to
                            the University Library in Copenhagen but it was on loan to <name
                                type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> when the library
                            burned down.</acquisition>
                    </history>
